%N A001570 Numbers k such that k^2 is centered hexagonal.
%C A001570 Chebyshev T-sequence with Diophantine property. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Nov 29 2002
%C A001570 a(n) = L(n,14), where L is defined as in A108299; see also A028230 for L(n,-14). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jun 01 2005
%C A001570 Numbers x satisfying x^2 + y^3 = (y+1)^3. Corresponding y given by A001921(n)={A028230(n)-1}/2. - _Lekraj Beedassy_, Jul 21 2006
%C A001570 Mod[ a(n), 12 ] = 1. (a(n) - 1)/12 = A076139(n) = Triangular numbers that are one-third of another triangular number. (a(n) - 1)/4 = A076140(n) = Triangular numbers T(k) that are three times another triangular number. - _Alexander Adamchuk_, Apr 06 2007
%C A001570 Also numbers n such that RootMeanSquare(1,3,...,2*n-1) is an integer. - _Ctibor O. Zizka_, Sep 04 2008
%C A001570 a(n), with n>1, is the length of the cevian of equilateral triangle whose side length is the term b(n) of the sequence A028230. This cevian divides the side (2*x+1) of the triangle in two integer segments x and x+1. - _Giacomo Fecondo_, Oct 09 2010
%C A001570 For n>=2, a(n) equals the permanent of the (2n-2)X(2n-2) tridiagonal matrix with sqrt(12)'s along the main diagonal, and 1's along the superdiagonal and the subdiagonal. - _John M. Campbell_, Jul 08 2011
%C A001570 Beal's conjecture would imply that set intersection of this sequence with the perfect powers (A001597) equals {1}. In other words, existence of a nontrivial perfect power in this sequence would disprove Beal's conjecture. - _Max Alekseyev_, Mar 15 2015
%C A001570 Numbers n such that there exists positive x with x^2 + x + 1 = 3n^2. - _Jeffrey Shallit_, Dec 11 2017
%C A001570 Given by the denominators of the continued fractions [1,(1,2)^i,3,(1,2)^{i-1},1]. - _Jeffrey Shallit_, Dec 11 2017
%C A001570 A near-isosceles integer-sided triangle with an angle of 2*Pi/3 is a triangle whose sides (a, a+1, c) satisfy Diophantine equation (a+1)^3 - a^3 = c^2. For n >= 2, the largest side c is given by a(n) while smallest and middle sides (a, a+1) = (A001921(n-1), A001922(n-1)) (see Julia link). - _Bernard Schott_, Nov 20 2022
